      h1.lead Composer Architecture
      p.lead I served as the lead designer on a cross-functional product squad alongside product managers, engineers, and analysts. Our mission was to stay one to two quarters ahead of development by proactively shaping the product backlog—evaluating epics, analyzing existing implementations, conducting user research, and delivering mockups that would guide future development.

      h2 Background: What Is Composer?
      p Composer is a core internal tool that enables car dealerships—and internal staff—to manage their websites. Tasks range from basic content updates to configuring complex site preferences. However, the tool had received minimal investment over the years, resulting in a clunky, unintuitive experience heavily reliant on hover states and overlay dialogs. It was ripe for modernization.


      img.full-width(src="img/composer-current.png" alt="Current State of Compoent Interface")
      .caption The current interface largely relies on hover states and overlays.

      h2 Strategic Framing
      p My initial challenge was to reimagine the future of Composer—not just visually, but behaviorally. Leveraging an existing design system helped eliminate decisions around color, spacing, and iconography, allowing me to focus on UX architecture and product usability. I created a foundational set of UX principles to guide the project and align the team:


      ol
        li Provide guidance throughout
        li Make good decisions easy
        li Aid users with tooling
        li Prioritize common decisions
        li Be accessible to all users
        li Intuitive for basic users, configurable for advanced
        li Ensure mobile parity
        li Keep users informed
        li Design for time-efficiency
        li Support tracking and tagging

      p These principles informed every design decision and helped us advocate for user-centered improvements across the tool.

      h3 User Research
      p To deeply understand the current pain points, I led an intensive two-day round of user interviews and observations. This included:
      ol 
        li Group interviews with four internal departments
        li Task-specific roundtable discussions
        li 1:1 shadow sessions to observe real-time behaviors and friction
      p These sessions uncovered dozens of opportunities for streamlining workflows. For example, simple preference toggles were implemented with dropdowns—even for binary true/false values. Replacing these with checkboxes reduced the number of clicks and improved scannability.


      img.full-width(src="img/composer-edit.png" alt="Composer in Edit Mode")
      img.full-width(src="img/compoer-library.png" alt="Composer Library")
      h3 Design Execution


      h4 Third-Party Tool
      p The first high-priority feature we tackled was the Third-Party Integration Manager, used to configure external tools and services supported by the platform.

      h4 Before:
      p A static dialog with a long, unorganized list of integrations. Users had to click into each item to access preferences, with documentation stored in a separate system.
      h4  After:
      p I redesigned this as a stand-alone, full-page application with:
      ol 
        li A searchable, categorized list of integrations on the left
        li Activated integrations visually elevated to the top
        li A contextual panel to the right for editing preferences
        li Embedded documentation available inline
      p This architecture preserves context, supports fast scanning and filtering, and dramatically reduces cognitive overhead. The design has already moved into implementation and is receiving positive early feedback.

      img.narrow(src="img/third-party-home.png" alt="Current Thrid Party Integration Home")
      .caption Currently, the "tool" is just a list of integrations.

      h3 Impact
      p The Composer overhaul demonstrates the value of aligning research, design, and architecture at the foundation level. My contributions created:

      ol 
        li A scalable UX framework for future work
        li A human-centered foundation for high-complexity tools
        li A tangible improvement in one of the system’s most used (and previously painful) features

